Here is what washing my hair is looking like these days! Its takes me 8 minutes in total to wash my hair while in the shower. I only do one round of shampoo and I focus on my scalp. This is one of my favorite things about being locked! As a loose natural, washing my hair took at least an hour between detangling, putting it in sections, prepping a clay wash, etc. and then styling would take the rest of the day! Now I wash and literally go on about my day. It is heaven.

Vacation Tips for microlocs:
1. Interlock before your trip so that you can swim all you want without worrying about your roots marrying at the bases
2. Do a thorough wash and moisturizing session before leaving home, bc you wont want to do that while traveling/having fun
3. Dont feel the need to wash your hair every day. You may be tempted if you are swimming every day, but this is not necessary, and will strip your hair. I typically rinse my hair with water after swimming in the ocean. If you are getting in chlorine, soak with water before entering the pool and you can wash with one round of shampoo if you plan on staying out of the chlorine for more than a day - otherwise rinse with water afterwards too. (This tip is just from personal experience. I tried washing everyday on one trip and my hair felt like a Brillo pad by the time I got home)
4. Give your hair a deep cleanse (several rounds of shampoo) the day you get home
5. MOST IMPORTANTLY: have fun and do all the things you want, stress free! Vacationing with locs is the best thing ever. My hair air dries perfectly, so i have no problems getting it wet or dirty when I’m on excursions or at the beach ❤️

I’m preparing to travel this week and wanted to share tips from past experiences. Please drop any extra tips that you’ve picked up along the way in the comments 😊❤️

Having just come home from Jamaica, I am reaffirmed in my decision to lock my hair. Vacations with my loose natural hair were soo miserable compared to the ease that my locs provide. Jumping in and out of the water with my hair done is my favorite part 😭. For my people on the fence. Just go ahead and loc it up ‼️‼️

I hate to be THAT person announcing my departure 💀 but I just wanted to give ya’ll a heads up that I will be MIA for the next 2 months. I am studying for the USMLE Step 1 exam (my first medical licensing exam) and since this test is a beast, I need to buckle down and pretend I don’t have a social media addiction. Hopefully I will see yall in May having passed this test and moved on to the next phase of my medical education 🖤🖤

My skin is by no means perfect, but its come a long way over the years. Here are the products I use:
1. Equate deep cleaning cream cleanser (contains salicylic acid) 
2. Equate benzoyl peroxide acne treatment gel
3. Advanced clinicals vitamin C serum
4. Equate daily facial moisturizer (SPF 15)
5. Vaseline (unscented)
6. GrandeLash MD serum (has a prostaglandin analogue)

If you are looking for a simple routine to start just do a cleanser, acne spot treatment, SPF, and vaseline!

Hope this is helpful!!

Sometimes the growth isn’t as dramatic as you want it to be!! And that’s okay. These are all one year apart. Wet hair in December of last year vs wet hair now. While I didn’t gain as much length as I expected, my hair looks more full and cohesive. I trimmed a few times this year trying to get the layers to even out and it has paid off! I love how full the weight line of my hair has become. You can see the top layer of my hair was near my collar bone last year and is near my armpit this year. I just wanted to share this small yearly difference to encourage anyone who didn’t make huge length gains this past year. Im sure your locs still changed in many other ways and you should celebrate that!! 

I just uploaded a new moisture routine video on YouTube if you are looking for ways to keep your locs soft and healthy as they grow and mature
